'''Nayef Aguerd''' ({{langx|ar|نايف أكرد}}; {{langx|ber|ⵏⴰⵢⴼ ⴰⴳⵕⴹ}}; born 30 March 1996) is a Moroccan professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-back]] for {{French football updater|Marseille}} club [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] and the [[Morocco national football team|Morocco national team]].

He began his professional career playing for [[Botola]] side [[Fath Union Sport|FUS Rabat]], before leaving to France and playing for [[Dijon FCO|Dijon]] and [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]]. He was chosen in Morocco's squads for the [[African Nations Championship]] in [[2018 African Nations Championship|2018]], the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] in [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations|2021]], [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|2023]] and [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations|2025]], and the [[FIFA World Cup]] in [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]].

== Early life ==
Nayef Aguerd was born and raised in the city of [[Kenitra]] in north western [[Morocco]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Eight things you need to know about Nayef Aguerd {{!}} West Ham United F.C. |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/eight-things-you-need-know-about-nayef-aguerd |access-date=2023-04-02 |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |language=en}}</ref>

Aguerd began his footballing career with the [[Mohammed VI Football Academy|Mohammed VI Academy]], before moving to [[Fath Union Sport|FUS Rabat]] in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Made in Morocco, Flourishing in France; Is London Calling For Nayef Aguerd? |date=9 June 2022 |url=https://breakingthelines.com/player-analysis/made-in-morocco-flourishing-in-france-is-london-calling-for-nayef-aguerd/ |access-date=18 June 2022}}</ref> The player then played a season with the club amateurs before signing his first professional contract with FUS Rabat in [[Botola]] in 2014.

==Club career==

=== Early career ===
During his first season with FUS Rabat, he was the runner-up of the 2015 Throne cup after losing the final against [[Olympique Club de Khouribga|Olympique de Khouribga]]. On 15 February 2015, he scored his first goal for the team in a 3–1 victory against [[Wydad AC]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Goalzz.com: live sports scores and news |url=https://www.goalzz.com/?player=111541 |access-date=6 March 2022 |website=goalzz.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Nayef Aguerd: Who is the Morocco international signed by West Ham United? {{!}} Goal.com English Bahrain |url=https://www.goal.com/en-bh/news/nayef-aguerd-who-is-the-morocco-international-signed-by-west-ham-united/bltaca3bd40a7cbde7c |access-date=2023-04-02 |website=Goal (website) |language=en-BH}}</ref> On 3 March, he scored his first continental goal in a 1–1 draw against [[UMS de Loum]].{{citation needed|date=September 2025}}

=== Dijon ===
After four seasons, he joined [[Dijon FCO|Dijon]] in [[Ligue 1]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dfco.fr/articles/82FE01A8-8394-4903-B88B-2530B3F0D51F|title=Nayef Aguerd première recrue du DFCO !|website=dfco.fr}}</ref> He made his professional debut with Dijon in a 4–0 win over [[OGC Nice|Nice]] on 25 August 2018, scoring the first goal for his side on his debut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/84637|title=LFP.fr – Ligue de Football Professionnel – Ligue 1 Conforama – Saison 2018/2019 – 3ème journée – OGC Nice / Dijon FCO|website=lfp.fr}}</ref>

=== Rennes ===
On 14 August 2020, Aguerd signed a contract with Ligue 1 team Rennes from Dijon for an undisclosed fee believed to be between €4m and €5m.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Official {{!}} Rennes sign central defender Nayef Aguerd {{!}} Get French Football News|url=https://www.getfootballnewsfrance.com/2020/official-rennes-sign-central-defender-nayef-aguerd/|access-date=1 January 2022|website=www.getfootballnewsfrance.com|date=14 August 2020 }}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a [[Friendlies|friendly]] against Nice; the game ended in a 3–2 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |title=A win to end preseason |url=https://www.ogcnice.com/fr/article/37014/a-win-to-end-preseason.html |access-date=6 March 2022 |website=OGC Nice |language=fr}}</ref> On 13 September 2020, Aguerd scored his first league goal in a 4–2 victory against [[Nîmes Olympique|Nîmes]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 September 2020 |title=Ligue 1: Guirassy Scores Twice as Rennes Beats Nimes 4–2; Marseille Down PSG 1–0 |url=https://www.news18.com/news/sports/guirassy-scores-twice-as-rennes-beats-nimes-4-2-monaco-wins-2874221.html |access-date=6 March 2022 |website=News18 |language=en}}</ref>

On 17 May 2021, He was placed 11th place in the [[Prix Marc-Vivien Foé]] as the best player who represents an African national football team in [[Ligue 1]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 May 2021 |title=Prix Marc-Vivien Foé: Gaël Kakuta, premier Lensois et Congolais sacré |url=https://www.rfi.fr/fr/afrique-foot/20210517-prix-marc-vivien-fo%C3%A9-ga%C3%ABl-kakuta-premier-lensois-et-congolais-sacr%C3%A9 |access-date=17 October 2022 |publisher=Radio France Internationale |language=fr}}</ref> On 19 August 2021, Aguerd scored a header, which marked his first European goal, in a 2–0 victory against [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Rennes v Rosenborg Live Commentary & Result, 19/08/21, UEFA Europa Conference League {{!}} Goal.com |url=https://www.goal.com/en-in/match/rennes-v-rosenborg/7r4glautwcqw9k7rvuaydj8d0 |access-date=6 March 2022 |website=Goal (website)}}</ref> A week later, Aguerd scored again in the second leg against Rosenborg in the [[2021–22 UEFA Europa Conference League qualifying phase and play-off round|2021–22 UEFA Europa Conference League play-off round]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Rosenborg vs. Stade Rennais – Football Match Summary – August 26, 2021 – ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/618183 |access-date=6 March 2022 |publisher=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> On 16 May 2022, Aguerd was placed 3rd as the best African player in [[Ligue 1]] for the [[Prix Marc-Vivien Foé]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 May 2022 |title=Prix Marc-Vivien Foé: l'Ivoirien Seko Fofana succède à Gaël Kakuta |url=https://www.rfi.fr/fr/afrique-foot/20220516-prix-marc-vivien-fo%C3%A9-l-ivoirien-seko-fofana-succ%C3%A8de-%C3%A0-ga%C3%ABl-kakuta |access-date=17 October 2022 |publisher=Radio France Internationale |language=fr}}</ref>

===West Ham United===
[[File:Nayef Aguerd (cropped) Wolves vs West Ham United Full Time.jpg|thumb|280x280px|Aguerd with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] in 2023.]]
In June 2022, Aguerd signed for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on a five-year contract for a fee of £30&nbsp;million. His fee was the fourth-highest paid by West Ham after those paid for [[Sébastien Haller]], [[Felipe Anderson]] and [[Kurt Zouma]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/61867137|title=West Ham complete £30m Aguerd signing from Rennes|work=BBC Sport|date=20 June 2022|access-date=20 June 2022}}</ref> On 16 July, Aguerd made his debut for the Hammers in a friendly against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], playing a total of 63 minutes of a 1–1 draw at the [[Madejski Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Highlights: Reading 1–1 West Ham United|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/highlights-reading-1-1-west-ham-united |date=17 July 2022 |access-date=17 July 2022 |publisher=West Ham United F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=16 July 2022 |title=David Moyes delivers Nayef Aguerd verdict after West Ham draw with Reading |url=https://www.hammers.news/pre-season/david-moyes-delivers-nayef-aguerd-verdict-after-west-ham-draw-with-reading/ |access-date=17 July 2022 |website=Hammers News}}</ref> In his second game, a pre-season friendly against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] on 19 July, Aguerd injured his ankle which required surgery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62298027|title=West Ham signing Aguerd has ankle surgery|work=BBC Sport|date=25 July 2022|access-date=25 July 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gorrie |first=Jonathan |date=21 October 2022 |title=West Ham handed boost as Nayef Aguerd appears to step up return from injury |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/west-ham-latest-news-aguerd-b1034509.html |access-date=25 October 2022 |work=Evening Standard}}</ref> On 19 October, Aguerd returned to training with the team three months after his injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Morocco's Aguerd edging closer to West Ham return |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/63314406 |date=19 October 2022 |access-date=25 October 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Morocco's Aguerd could play for West Ham before World Cup, says Moyes |url=https://gulfnews.com/qatar-world-cup-2022/news-views/moroccos-aguerd-could-play-for-west-ham-before-world-cup-says-moyes-1.91362755 |date=19 October 2022 |access-date=25 October 2022 |website=Gulf News}}</ref> He made his competitive West Ham United debut on 27 October in a [[2022–23 UEFA Europa Conference League group stage|Europa Conference League]] game against [[Silkeborg IF|Silkeborg]], which West Ham won 1–0.<ref name="WHUDebut">{{cite web | title=West Ham reach last 16 after win over Silkeborg | work=BBC Sport | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63404741 |date=27 October 2022 | access-date=28 October 2022}}</ref> On 2 April, Aguerd scored his first Premier League goal in the home encounter against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], which ended in a 1–0 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 April 2023 |title=المغربي أكرد يهدي وست هام فوزاً مصيرياً |url=https://www.hespress.com/المغربي-أكرد-يهدي-وست-هام-فوزاً-مصيريا-1148001.html |access-date=2023-04-02 |website=Hespress – هسبريس جريدة إلكترونية مغربية |language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Steinberg |first=Jacob |date=2 April 2023 |title=Nayef Aguerd gives West Ham vital win over Southampton to lift survival fight |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/apr/02/west-ham-southampton-premier-league-match-report |access-date=2023-04-02 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 7 June, Aguerd won his first major trophy for the club the [[2022–23 UEFA Europa Conference League]] against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], which ended in a 2–1 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |title=West Ham lift first major trophy in more than 40 years after beating Fiorentina in Europa Conference League final |url=https://news.sky.com/story/west-ham-lift-first-major-trophy-in-more-than-40-years-after-beating-fiorentina-in-europa-conference-league-final-12898462 |access-date=2023-06-08 |publisher=Sky News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=West Ham win dramatic Europa Conference League final |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65826820 |access-date=2023-06-08}}</ref>
He left the club in September 2025. He played 61 games in all competitions in his three seasons with West Ham.<ref name="marseille">{{cite web |date=2 September 2025 |title=Aguerd departs |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/aguerd-departs |access-date=2 September 2025 |website=West Ham United F.C.}}</ref>

====Loan to Real Sociedad====
On 30 August 2024, Aguerd was loaned to [[La Liga]] club [[Real Sociedad]] for the 2024–25 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nayef Aguerd heads to Real Sociedad on loan |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/nayef-aguerd-heads-real-sociedad-loan |publisher=West Ham United Football Club |access-date=30 August 2024 |date=30 August 2024 }}</ref>

===Marseille===
On 1 September 2025, Aguerd returned to [[Ligue 1]], as he signed a contract with [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] until 2030 for a fee reported to be "around €23 million".<ref name="marseille" /><ref>{{cite web | last=Alami | first=Aymen | title=Aguerd Completes Marseille Move | website=Morocco World News | date=1 September 2025 | url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2025/09/256299/aguerd-completes-marseille-move/ | access-date=2 September 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:AguerdYoussef (cropped).jpg|thumb|200px|Aguerd with [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] in 2023]]
Aguerd made his debut for the [[Morocco national football team|Morocco national team]] in a friendly 0–0 tie with [[Albania national football team|Albania]] on 31 August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mountakhab.net/www/modules/fiches_joueurs/feuille_match.php?id=1233492|title=Rapport de match: Albanie 0–0 Maroc|first=Achraf|last=Bakkali|website=Mountakhab.net|access-date=25 August 2018|archive-date=26 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826043843/http://mountakhab.net/www/modules/fiches_joueurs/feuille_match.php?id=1233492|url-status=dead}}</ref> Aguerd represented Morocco in the [[2018 African Nations Championship]], helping his country to achieve their first CHAN title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42939957|title=Hosts Morocco crowned CHAN champions|work=BBC Sport }}</ref> On 6 September 2021, Aguerd scored his first goal against [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]] in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF second round|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]], he sent a sharp shot in the net from a cross.<ref>{{Cite web |title=الشوط الأول من مباراة المنتخب ضد السودان.. استحواذ كلي للأسود ونايف أكرد يسجل هدف التقدم للفريق الوطني |url=https://www.elbotola.com/article/2021-09-02-19-55-361.html |access-date=6 March 2022 |website=elbotola.com |language=Ar}}</ref>

He was later invited by [[Vahid Halilhodžić]] to represent Morocco in the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=23 December 2021|title=Vahid Halilhodzic reveals final list of players for CAN 2022|url=https://en.hespress.com/32767-vahid-halilhodzic-reveals-final-list-of-players-for-can-2022.html|access-date=11 January 2022|website=HESPRESS English – Morocco's leading digital media|language=en-US}}</ref> Nayef started all of the matches in the group stages<ref>{{Cite web|title=Africa Cup of Nations (Sky Sports)|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/morocco-vs-ghana/teams/457198|access-date=28 January 2022|website=Sky Sports|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Africa Cup of Nations (Sky Sports)|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/morocco-vs-comoros/teams/457210|access-date=28 January 2022|website=Sky Sports|language=en}}</ref> and scored an own-goal in a 2–2 draw against [[Gabon national football team|Gabon]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Gabon v Morocco Match Report, 18/01/2022, Africa Cup of Nations {{!}} Goal.com|url=https://www.goal.com/en/match/gabon-v-morocco/7o6548ig1nn0zm2jg1tsh7504|access-date=28 January 2022|website=Goal (website)}}</ref>

On 10 November 2022, he was named in Morocco's 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Morocco World Cup 2022 squad: Who's in and who's out? {{!}} Goal.com |url=https://www.goal.com/en-bh/lists/morocco-2022-world-cup-squad-hakimi-ziyech-mazraoui-qatar/blta36257fc4feeb66a |access-date=10 November 2022 |website=Goal (website)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=10 November 2022 |title=Moroccan coach unveils list of 26 Atlas Lions in 2022 World Cup |url=https://en.hespress.com/52697-moroccan-coach-unveils-list-of-26-atlas-lions-in-2022-world-cup.html |access-date=10 November 2022 |website=HESPRESS English – Morocco News |language=en-US}}</ref> Aguerd played all three group games and the Round of 16 match against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] alongside [[Romain Saïss]] and Morocco conceded only once in those four matches, through an own goal by Aguerd. However, he missed both the quarter-final victory over [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] through injury and then the decisive game against [[France national football team|France]] due to illness – he was withdrawn minutes before kick-off in the semi-final, despite having been listed in the official starting line-ups.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Simmonds |first=Kadeem |date=15 December 2022 |title=Walid Regragui says Nayef Aguerd missed Morocco's semi-final loss due to the flu|url=https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/news/nayef-aguerd-france-semi-final-25757484 |access-date=2022-12-24 |website=Football.London |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Winehouse |first=Amitai |title=Morocco's Aguerd pulls out of semi-final before kick-off |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4002465/2022/12/14/aguerd-morocco-world-cup-injury/ |access-date=2022-12-24 |website=The Athletic |date=14 December 2022 |language=en}}</ref>

On 28 December 2023, Aguerd was among the 27 players selected by coach [[Walid Regragui]] to represent Morocco in the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 December 2023 |title=Regragui unveils 27 player list for Morocco's participation in CAN 2023 |url=https://en.hespress.com/77181-regragui-unveils-27-player-list-for-moroccos-participation-in-can-2023.html |access-date=2023-12-29 |website=HESPRESS English – Morocco News |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=28 December 2023 |title=Regragui names 27 provisional players for AFCON |url=https://www.cafonline.com/caf-africa-cup-of-nations/news/regragui-names-27-provisional-players-for-afcon/ |access-date=2023-12-29 |website=CAF |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 11 December 2025, Aguerd was called up to the Morocco squad for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/morocco-name-star-studded-afcon-squad-as-hakimi-makes-cut-but-diop-misses-out/|title=Morocco name star-studded AFCON squad as Hakimi makes cut but Diop misses out|publisher=[[Confederation of African Football]]|date=11 December 2025|access-date=12 December 2025}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
On 9 September 2023, Aguerd along with his [[Morocco national football team|national teammates]] donated some of their blood for the needy affected by the [[2023 Marrakesh-Safi earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Patrick | first=Holly | title=Moroccan national footballers donate blood to help earthquake victims | publisher=Independent TV | date=11 September 2023 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/tv/news/morocco-earthquake-football-blood-donation-b2408997.html | access-date=11 September 2023}}</ref>

